1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,140
In Python, there are several ways to pass arguments into functions,

2

00:00:04,140  -->  00:00:06,755
each with its own advantages and trade-offs.

3

00:00:06,755  -->  00:00:08,875
Let's explore these one-by-one;

4

00:00:08,875  -->  00:00:12,680
positional, keyword, and mixed argument passing.

5

00:00:12,680  -->  00:00:16,060
Positional arguments are passed in a specific order,

6

00:00:16,060  -->  00:00:19,890
matching the order of parameters in the function definition.

7

00:00:19,890  -->  00:00:24,120
Here, the function uses the values based on their positions.

8

00:00:24,120  -->  00:00:25,940
In mixed argument passing,

9

00:00:25,940  -->  00:00:29,980
this is a mix of positional and keyword arguments in a single function call.

10

00:00:29,980  -->  00:00:32,100
An important note about this one,

11

00:00:32,100  -->  00:00:35,260
is that positional arguments must come before keyword arguments,

12

00:00:35,260  -->  00:00:36,720
or there will be an error.

13

00:00:36,720  -->  00:00:39,400
Finally, we have keyword arguments where we

14

00:00:39,400  -->  00:00:42,440
specify the parameter name along with the value,

15

00:00:42,440  -->  00:00:45,740
allowing you to pass arguments in any order.

16

00:00:45,740  -->  00:00:49,160
This is my personal favorite method for defining arguments.

17

00:00:49,160  -->  00:00:54,590
Let's see some examples of these different ways to pass in arguments into our functions.

18

00:00:54,590  -->  00:00:56,300
Let's talk about positional,

19

00:00:56,300  -->  00:00:58,970
keyword, and mixed argument passing.

20

00:00:58,970  -->  00:01:01,700
First, positional arguments.

21

00:01:01,700  -->  00:01:04,020
When it comes to positional arguments,

22

00:01:04,020  -->  00:01:08,640
the order of the parameters to be used by the function are extremely important,

23

00:01:08,640  -->  00:01:10,985
as we'll see in this function.

24

00:01:10,985  -->  00:01:13,580
We'll write a function called describe_trip,

25

00:01:13,580  -->  00:01:17,260
and we'll see why positional arguments are so important.

26

00:01:17,260  -->  00:01:20,800
When we write def describe_trip,

27

00:01:21,290  -->  00:01:27,960
we'll pass in city and days into the function as parameters,

28

00:01:27,960  -->  00:01:29,870
and then we'll say return,

29

00:01:29,870  -->  00:01:32,710
and we'll return an f string and say,

30

00:01:32,710  -->  00:01:43,160
we'll spend in squiggly brackets days in city.

31

00:01:45,410  -->  00:01:50,430
You'll spend days in blank, which would be the city.

32

00:01:50,430  -->  00:01:58,710
By calling this function with describe_trip, we'll say Paris,

33

00:01:58,740  -->  00:02:02,680
five, this will place Paris into

34

00:02:02,680  -->  00:02:09,260
the city position and five into the days position, as we'll see here.

35

00:02:09,260  -->  00:02:12,825
Our output will say, you'll spend five days in Paris.

36

00:02:12,825  -->  00:02:18,045
However, what if we were to reverse the argument order like this?

37

00:02:18,045  -->  00:02:22,850
Now our arguments are in reverse order like this.

38

00:02:22,850  -->  00:02:25,410
Can you guess what the output of this is going to be?

39

00:02:25,410  -->  00:02:30,150
When we run this, we'll see you'll spend Paris days in five.

40

00:02:30,150  -->  00:02:32,370
Now the output is reversed.

41

00:02:32,370  -->  00:02:34,970
As you can see, order matters a lot here,

42

00:02:34,970  -->  00:02:37,170
because if you switch the arguments around,

43

00:02:37,170  -->  00:02:39,230
you'll get a completely different result,

44

00:02:39,230  -->  00:02:43,110
perhaps even one that's unintentional or full of errors,

45

00:02:43,110  -->  00:02:45,590
like we just saw in the second example,

46

00:02:45,590  -->  00:02:47,240
going from here to here.

47

00:02:47,240  -->  00:02:50,220
Next up is keyword arguments.

48

00:02:50,220  -->  00:02:54,840
Keyword arguments specify the parameter name along with the value,

49

00:02:54,840  -->  00:02:57,980
allowing you to pass arguments in any order.

50

00:02:57,980  -->  00:03:02,120
This is personally my favorite way to define parameters for my functions,

51

00:03:02,120  -->  00:03:05,180
because while it is more verbose and requires more writing,

52

00:03:05,180  -->  00:03:07,480
it helps to add a layer of structure and

53

00:03:07,480  -->  00:03:11,840
accountability to how functions should be defined and how they should work.

54

00:03:11,840  -->  00:03:15,340
You never have to worry about the order of the inputs because

55

00:03:15,340  -->  00:03:19,240
you explicitly define what they are right from the get go.

56

00:03:19,240  -->  00:03:21,820
For example, this is how we would assign

57

00:03:21,820  -->  00:03:25,200
keyword arguments to our described trip function.

58

00:03:25,990  -->  00:03:30,000
We'll write this function, and then what we'll do is,

59

00:03:30,000  -->  00:03:32,680
we'll re-declare this function.

60

00:03:35,220  -->  00:03:39,720
Now what we'll do is when we are defining our arguments,

61

00:03:39,720  -->  00:03:46,370
we'll say days equal five and city equals Paris.

62

00:03:46,370  -->  00:03:50,540
Now, even though these are reversed in the previous example,

63

00:03:50,540  -->  00:03:53,310
when we print this, we'll now see,

64

00:03:53,310  -->  00:03:55,950
you'll spend five days in Paris.

65

00:03:55,950  -->  00:03:59,820
We can also assign default to our function as well to make sure that

66

00:03:59,820  -->  00:04:03,900
our functions parameters always have a default value.

67

00:04:03,900  -->  00:04:06,320
We'll learn more about this in the next section,

68

00:04:06,320  -->  00:04:09,725
but here's a quick introduction to this concept.

69

00:04:09,725  -->  00:04:13,000
What we can do is that we can take our function like this,

70

00:04:13,000  -->  00:04:17,190
and we could say city equals Paris,

71

00:04:17,190  -->  00:04:21,765
and days equals five.

72

00:04:21,765  -->  00:04:26,585
Our two parameters now have default inputs, Paris, and five.

73

00:04:26,585  -->  00:04:30,985
Even if we were to print just a simple describe_trip,

74

00:04:30,985  -->  00:04:32,380
we'll execute this code.

75

00:04:32,380  -->  00:04:37,840
We'll then not pass in any arguments into the described trip function but if we run this,

76

00:04:37,840  -->  00:04:41,440
we'll now see you'll spend five days in Paris.

77

00:04:41,440  -->  00:04:43,920
So we didn't need to input

78

00:04:43,920  -->  00:04:48,240
those values because they are the defaults if we do not pass anything into them.

79

00:04:48,240  -->  00:04:50,660
Now, we could still define whatever we want.

80

00:04:50,660  -->  00:04:55,120
For example, let's say that we copy this from earlier,

81

00:04:55,120  -->  00:05:01,960
and we say days is 10, and city is Norway.

82

00:05:02,750  -->  00:05:06,795
Now we see you'll spend 10 days in Norway.

83

00:05:06,795  -->  00:05:13,630
But, we still have those default values attached to the parameters as backups,

84

00:05:13,630  -->  00:05:16,815
just in case we were to not include a keyword argument.

85

00:05:16,815  -->  00:05:25,240
If we were to write describe_trip days equals 10,

86

00:05:25,240  -->  00:05:27,570
the output will be,

87

00:05:27,570  -->  00:05:29,850
you'll spend 10 days in Paris,

88

00:05:29,850  -->  00:05:32,910
because Paris is still the default value for city,

89

00:05:32,910  -->  00:05:38,335
but we've updated the days from what the default is of five to now 10.

90

00:05:38,335  -->  00:05:41,170
Now let's talk about mixed argument passing.

91

00:05:41,170  -->  00:05:45,870
You can also mix positional and keyword arguments in a single function call.

92

00:05:45,870  -->  00:05:50,605
However, positional arguments must come before keyword arguments.

93

00:05:50,605  -->  00:05:55,770
Let's re-initialize this function again with no default argument values.

94

00:05:55,770  -->  00:05:58,610
We'll just take our code from before,

95

00:05:58,610  -->  00:06:02,605
and we will re-run the cell,

96

00:06:02,605  -->  00:06:10,260
and then now if we were to say describe trip,

97

00:06:10,260  -->  00:06:12,740
and we pass in again,

98

00:06:12,740  -->  00:06:15,780
our original input, which was Paris,

99

00:06:15,880  -->  00:06:19,765
and days equal five,

100

00:06:19,765  -->  00:06:23,580
now we'll see, you'll spend five days in Paris.

101

00:06:23,580  -->  00:06:28,700
But this will not work if we were to do this in reverse.

102

00:06:28,700  -->  00:06:33,245
If we were to take days and put this before Paris,

103

00:06:33,245  -->  00:06:36,780
since they are mixed arguments,

104

00:06:36,780  -->  00:06:38,820
we'll get a syntax error,

105

00:06:38,820  -->  00:06:42,500
and it'll say positional argument follows keyword argument.

106

00:06:42,500  -->  00:06:46,700
This will not work. Always be careful to define

107

00:06:46,700  -->  00:06:51,480
the positional arguments with no argument equals something first,

108

00:06:51,480  -->  00:06:53,800
and then include the keyword arguments.

109

00:06:53,800  -->  00:06:56,790
Argument equals a value after.

110

00:06:56,790  -->  00:06:59,800
Using mixed arguments offers flexibility

111

00:06:59,800  -->  00:07:03,645
while ensuring that required positional arguments are provided first.

112

00:07:03,645  -->  00:07:06,440
Personally, I find this one a bit more confusing,

113

00:07:06,440  -->  00:07:09,640
but it's important to know how to work with this method.

114

00:07:09,640  -->  00:07:11,460
If you end up seeing this in code,

115

00:07:11,460  -->  00:07:13,560
you get from your team or are working on

116

00:07:13,560  -->  00:07:17,220
functions where this method works for you. Great work.
